sentences: Michael John Campion (born December 4, 1962) is an American songwriter, music producer and entrepreneur.
In 1980, Campion formed "Surf City" (originally "The Surf City Boys"), a band focusing on the music of The Beach Boys and Jan and Dean.
Campion and Kirsch reunited in 2005 to release a gospel vocal album, under the name of "Feather".

In 1986 Campion bought into a boutique music store concept called "L.A.B. Sound" and opened a location in Orange County, that strategically shared a wall with a recording studio owned by Frontline Records.
Campion met Steve Ridinger of EVETS Corporation in 1992.
Musicians had been deprived from Danelectro products for nearly 30 years, when Campion and Ridinger introduced 3 new pedals under the brand name, at the Winter NAMM Show, in 1997.

Campion left Danelectro in 2002 and dove back into songwriting, placing songs in a few television shows, like One Tree Hill, through agencies that demanded to own the song's publishing, in exchange for their placement efforts.
Feeling that this was unfair, Campion formed "Music Epicenter", with partner and mentor songsmith, Chris Falson in 2003.
In 2011, Campion struck a deal with Rainbow S.r.l. to develop a music television series as a platform for Kalina and Kiana's music career.
The show (recast) premiered in 2016 as Maggie & Bianca: Fashion Friends.
Campion married Lezlie Gibbs in 1988.

In a rapid, but thorough design and development effort, Danelectro released their first model of guitar, (a replica of the 1956 "U2"), exactly one year later The Danelectro U2 was embraced by the industry and the demand for additional models set the course for the years to follow.
In 1980, Campion formed "Surf City" (originally "The Surf City Boys"), a band focusing on the music of The Beach Boys and Jan and Dean.
Stamos would later introduce Campion to The Beach Boys and Jan and Dean, with whom Campion would later tour.

Under the name of "Pacific Productions", Campion would spend the next couple of years writing and producing dozens of jingles and music campaigns, often calling upon the vocal talents of Beach Boys' band members like Jeffrey Foskett and Phil Bardowell.
Musicians had been deprived from Danelectro products for nearly 30 years, when Campion and Ridinger introduced 3 new pedals under the brand name, at the Winter NAMM Show, in 1997.
In their three years together, The Raymies performed over 100 live shows from Los Angeles to New York and recorded nearly 40 songs.
